CA1829.shortDescription: Use Length/Count property instead of Count() when available
CA1829.fullDescription: Enumerable.Count() potentially enumerates the sequence while a Length/Count property is a direct access.

CA2254.shortDescription: Template should be a static expression
CA2254.fullDescription: The logging message template should not vary between calls.

CS1591.shortDescription: Missing XML comment for publicly visible type or member
CS1591.fullDescription: The /doc compiler option was specified, but one or more constructs did not have comments.

CS1998.shortDescription: Async method lacks 'await' operators and will run synchronously

S101.shortDescription: Types should be named in PascalCase
S101.fullDescription: Shared naming conventions allow teams to collaborate efficiently.

S1118.shortDescription: Utility classes should not have public constructors
S1118.fullDescription: Whenever there are portions of code that are duplicated and do not depend on the state of their container class, they can be centralized inside a "utility class". A utility class is a class that only has static members, hence it should not be instantiated.

S1155.shortDescription: "Any()" should be used to test for emptiness
S1155.fullDescription: When you call Any(), it clearly communicates the codes intention, which is to check if the collection is empty. Using Count() == 0 for this purpose is less direct and makes the code slightly more complex. However, there are some cases where special attention should be paid:

S125.shortDescription: Sections of code should not be commented out
S125.fullDescription: Commented-out code distracts the focus from the actual executed code. It creates a noise that increases maintenance code. And because it is never executed, it quickly becomes out of date and invalid.

S1481.shortDescription: Unused local variables should be removed
S1481.fullDescription: An unused local variable is a variable that has been declared but is not used anywhere in the block of code where it is defined. It is dead code, contributing to unnecessary complexity and leading to confusion when reading the code. Therefore, it should be removed from your code to maintain clarity and efficiency.

S2094.fullDescription: There is no good excuse for an empty class. If its being used simply as a common extension point, it should be replaced with an interface. If it was stubbed in as a placeholder for future development it should be fleshed-out. In any other case, it should be eliminated.

S2971.fullDescription: In the interests of readability, code that can be simplified should be simplified. To that end, there are several ways IEnumerable language integrated queries (LINQ) can be simplified. This not only improves readabilty but can also lead to improved performance.

S3168.fullDescription: An async method with a void return type does not follow the task asynchronous programming (TAP) model since the return type should be Task or Task<TResult>

S4487.fullDescription: Private fields which are written but never read are a case of "dead store". Changing the value of such a field is useless and most probably indicates an error in the code.
